						               													<description>Space Race is a simple card game designed for two players, though more can play with additional card sets (as there is no player interaction whatsoever).&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The object of the game is to complete a round trip through the Solar System by drawing ten planet cards in their proper order. (The order will be unfamiliar, though, as it goes Earth -&amp;gt; Saturn -&amp;gt; Jupiter -&amp;gt; Mars -&amp;gt; Uranus -&amp;gt; Neptune -&amp;gt; Venus -&amp;gt; Mercury -&amp;gt; Earth). Each card features well executed art done in a style similar to golden age science fiction pulp magazines.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game consists of two identical decks with cards numbered 1-10. These cards represent round trips the the Solar System, starting with &amp;quot;Take Off&amp;quot; (Card 1) and ending with &amp;quot;Landing On Earth&amp;quot; (Card 10). Players take a deck and shuffle it, then place it before them. The first player draws a card. If it is &amp;quot;Take Off&amp;quot; (Card 1), they place it in front of them and draw the next card. If the next card is a planet but not Card 2, they discard it in a discard pile next to their original pile and draw again, until they draw a card that says &amp;quot;Next player goes&amp;quot;. The next player takes a turn, and draws until they get a &amp;quot;Next player goes&amp;quot; card. Chance cards such as &amp;quot;lost on the moon,&amp;quot; &amp;quot;Sputnik,&amp;quot; and &amp;quot;Danger--Comets&amp;quot; can affect a player's turn.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Players may draw from either pile, so there is a memory element, as you must remember which pile your next planetary target was in.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;All cards must be discarded in the pile next to the pile from which they were drawn.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The goal is to collect all 10 cards, in sequence.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Rules list a variant for three or more players through using multiple copies of the game.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
